<div id="review_3142246646" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3142246646" />
    <a title="Ken" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/38999260-ken"><img alt="Ken" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1446483502p2/38999260.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3142246646?book_show_action=true">Jan 15, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ken" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ken" href="/user/show/38999260-ken">Ken</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780571342211" href="/book/show/35718747-the-children-of-men">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3142246646" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer18040368506562975922">This was another novel on the list of movie adaptations that I really enjoyed and wanted to see how the original source material compared.<br/>Admittedly it’s been so long since I’ve seen the 2006 film but remember it enough to know that the premise are the same but each has a completely different feel.<br/><br/>The main crux is the human population can no longer reproduce, with the last child born 25 years previous and how it impacts on society.<br/><br/>With the story set during 2021 it couldn’t have been more timely,</span>
  <span id="freeText18040368506562975922" style="display:none">This was another novel on the list of movie adaptations that I really enjoyed and wanted to see how the original source material compared.<br />Admittedly it’s been so long since I’ve seen the 2006 film but remember it enough to know that the premise are the same but each has a completely different feel.<br /><br />The main crux is the human population can no longer reproduce, with the last child born 25 years previous and how it impacts on society.<br /><br />With the story set during 2021 it couldn’t have been more timely, I definitely feel that there’s a disconnect with Baby Boomers and Millennials today - so a novel that explores themes of an ageing population without a new up and coming group just highlighted how the young and old complement and need each other.<br /><br />From a maternal instinct of those doting on pets and the need for sex having been diminished to the elderly becoming more of a hindrance to a declining work force, James vividly creates a dysfunctional landscape perfectly.<br /><br />The book is certainly a lot slower paced which actually aided the story that James is trying to tell. <br />The gradual decent into chaos as people lose focuses as inevitable but distant end is more clearly felt.<br /><br />It’s one of them great occurrences where both the book and movie can be enjoyed separately.</span>
  <a data-text-id="18040368506562975922" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


